}
</style>
<small>shape: (5,)</small><table border="1" class="dataframe"><thead><tr><th></th></tr><tr><td>i32</td></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>0</td></tr><tr><td>1</td></tr><tr><td>2</td></tr><tr><td>3</td></tr><tr><td>4</td></tr></tbody></table></div>
```
:::
:::


### Named Series

Series can be named:

::: {#8cf74a97 .cell execution_count=3}
``` {.python .cell-code}
s3 = pl.Series("Name", ["Bob", "Luc", "Lucy"])

s3
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=3}
```{=html}
<div><style>
.dataframe > thead > tr,
.dataframe > tbody > tr {
  text-align: right;
  white-space: pre-wrap;
}
</style>
<small>shape: (3,)</small><table border="1" class="dataframe"><thead><tr><th>Name</th></tr><tr><td>str</td></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>&quot;Bob&quot;</td></tr><tr><td>&quot;Luc&quot;</td></tr><tr><td>&quot;Lucy&quot;</td></tr></tbody></table></div>
```
:::
:::


## DataFrames

DataFrames are **two-dimensional and composed of named Series of equal lengths**. This means that DataFrames are heterogeneous, but that columns contain homogeneous data.

They can be created from:

- lists of Series:

::: {#578c8d61 .cell execution_count=4}
``` {.python .cell-code}
df1 = pl.DataFrame([s3, pl.Series("Colour", ["Red", "Green", "Blue"])])

df1
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=4}
```{=html}
<div><style>
.dataframe > thead > tr,
.dataframe > tbody > tr {
  text-align: right;
  white-space: pre-wrap;
}
</style>
<small>shape: (3, 2)</small><table border="1" class="dataframe"><thead><tr><th>Name</th><th>Colour</th></tr><tr><td>str</td><td>str</td></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>&quot;Bob&quot;</td><td>&quot;Red&quot;</td></tr><tr><td>&quot;Luc&quot;</td><td>&quot;Green&quot;</td></tr><tr><td>&quot;Lucy&quot;</td><td>&quot;Blue&quot;</td></tr></tbody></table></div>
```
:::
:::


- dictionaries:

::: {#9ed8aa2e .cell execution_count=5}
``` {.python .cell-code}
from datetime import date

df2 = pl.DataFrame(
    {
        "Date": [
            date(2024, 10, 1),
            date(2024, 10, 2),
            date(2024, 10, 3),
            date(2024, 10, 6)
        ],
        "Rain": [2.1, 0.5, 0.0, 1.8],
        "Cloud cover": [1, 1, 0, 2]
        }
    )

df2
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=5}
```{=html}
<div><style>
.dataframe > thead > tr,
.dataframe > tbody > tr {
  text-align: right;
  white-space: pre-wrap;
}
</style>
<small>shape: (4, 3)</small><table border="1" class="dataframe"><thead><tr><th>Date</th><th>Rain</th><th>Cloud cover</th></tr><tr><td>date</td><td>f64</td><td>i64</td></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>2024-10-01</td><td>2.1</td><td>1</td></tr><tr><td>2024-10-02</td><td>0.5</td><td>1</td></tr><tr><td>2024-10-03</td><td>0.0</td><td>0</td></tr><tr><td>2024-10-06</td><td>1.8</td><td>2</td></tr></tbody></table></div>
```
:::
:::


- NumPy ndarrays:

::: {#ba7b3d48 .cell execution_count=6}
``` {.python .cell-code}
import numpy as np

df3 = pl.DataFrame(np.array([(1, 2), (3, 4)]))

df3
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=6}
```{=html}
<div><style>
.dataframe > thead > tr,
.dataframe > tbody > tr {
