</style>
<small>shape: (2, 2)</small><table border="1" class="dataframe"><thead><tr><th>column_0</th><th>column_1</th></tr><tr><td>i64</td><td>i64</td></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>2</td></tr><tr><td>3</td><td>4</td></tr></tbody></table></div>
```
:::
:::


Because NumPy ndarrays are stored in memory by rows, the values in the first dimension of the array fill in the first row. If you want to fill in the DataFrame by column, you use the `orient` parameter:

::: {#d2b5c9ae .cell execution_count=7}
``` {.python .cell-code}
df4 = pl.DataFrame(np.array([(1, 2), (3, 4)]), orient="col")

df4
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=7}
```{=html}
<div><style>
.dataframe > thead > tr,
.dataframe > tbody > tr {
  text-align: right;
  white-space: pre-wrap;
}
</style>
<small>shape: (2, 2)</small><table border="1" class="dataframe"><thead><tr><th>column_0</th><th>column_1</th></tr><tr><td>i64</td><td>i64</td></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>3</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td>4</td></tr></tbody></table></div>
```
:::
:::


To specify column names, you can use the schema parameter:

::: {#8efc5069 .cell execution_count=8}
``` {.python .cell-code}
df5 = pl.DataFrame(np.array([(1, 2), (3, 4)]), schema=["Var1", "Var2"])

df5
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=8}
```{=html}
<div><style>
.dataframe > thead > tr,
.dataframe > tbody > tr {
  text-align: right;
